Pandas

Pandas

  • Python Data Analysis Library
  • originally written by Wes McKinney
  • creates a Python object with rows and columns called data frame

Loading and Saving Data with Pandas

  • convert a Python’s list, dictionary or Numpy array to a Pandas data frame
  • open a local file using Pandas, usually a CSV file, but could also be a delimited text file (like TSV), Excel, etc
  • open a remote file or database like a CSV or a JSONon a website through a URL or read from a SQL table/database
  • what about SPSS files:
    • convert them to csv or excel
    • use savReaderWriter module

Basic exploratory commands

  • df.head(n): n first rows
  • df.tail(n): n last rows
  • df.shape: the number of rows and columns
  • df.info(): the index, datatype and memory information
  • s.value_counts(dropna=False): would allow you to view unique values and counts for a series
  • df.describe(): summary statistics for numerical columns
  • df.corr(): correlation between columns in a data frame

Subsetting

  • df[col]: return column with label col as Series
  • df[[col1, col2]]: returns columns as a new DataFrame
  • df.iloc[0,:]: selecting first row
  • df.iloc[0,0]: selecting the first element of the first column

Lab

  • Print the second row of the master DF
  • Print from the 10th row till 20th row (included)
  • Print weight and height columns
  • Print the 4th row of the weight and height columns
  • Print the 10th element of the weight column

Filter, sort and groupby

  • df[df[column] > value]: all rows where column is greater than value
  • &: and ; |: or; df[(df[column1] > value1) & (df[column2<value2])]
  • df.sort_values(column1): sorting DF by column1 ASC (default)
  • df.sort_values(column2,ascending=False): sorting DF by column1 DESC
  • df.sort_values([column1,column2],ascending=[True,False]): sorting by 2 columns
  • df.groupby(column): involves splitting the data into groups based on some criteria, applying a function to each group independently and combining the results into a data structure
  • df.groupby([column1,column2])

Renaming

  • df.rename()
  • (index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, …)
  • df.rename(index=str, {columns={“A”: “a”, “B”: “c”})
  • (mapper, axis={‘index’, ‘columns’}, …)
  • df.rename({“A”: “a”, “C”: “c”}, axis=‘columns’)
  • df.rename(columns={“A”: “a”, “C”: “c”})

Lab

  • Calculate players’ mean height and mean weight by birthState for players, who were born in USA after 1950.
  • Print only birthState, mean height and weight sorted by birthState DESC.
  • HINT: df.mean() returns mean for all columns.
  • Rename columns to State, AverageW and AverageH.

Solution

  • columns=[“birthCountry”,“birthState”,“birthYear”,“height”,“weight”]
  • selecting columns:df1=df[columns]
  • selecting rows: df1=df1[(df[“birthCountry”]==“USA”) & (df[“birthYear”]>1950)]
  • grouping and calculating mean: df1=df1.groupby(“birthState”).mean().iloc[:,1:3]
  • sorting: df1=df1.sort_values(“birthState”,ascending=False)
  • renaming: df1.rename(columns={“height”:“AVheight”,“weight”:“AVweight”})

Interactive jupyter widgets (2)

  • using i.e.:
@interact
def ShowNRows(x=10):
    return df.head(x)
  • defining boundaries and steps for x
@interact
def ShowNRows(x=(1,len(df),10)):
    return df.head(x)
  • defining columns
@interact
def ShowNRows(column=["height","weight"],x=(1,len(df),100)):
    return df[column].head(x)

Data Cleaning

  • pd.isnull(): checking for null values
  • df[df.column.isnull()]: returns DF with rows, where column has null values
  • pd.isnull().sum(): how many null values
  • df.dropna(): drop missing values (rows) (axis=1 columns)
  • df.fillna(x): replace missing values with x
  • s.fillna(s.mean()): replace missing values with the mean
  • df.column.fillna(df.column.mean(), inplace=True): replacing null values in column with mean of this column and saving the result immediately (inplace=True)

Lab

  • Show 10 rows of Master DF, where weight is null.
  • Replace null values in weight column with average.
  • Print the average value and the 20th row from Master DF.

Solution

  • selecting columns: df[df.weight.isnull()].head(10)
  • calculating average: averageW=df[“weight”].mean()
  • replacing with inplace: df.weight.fillna(averageW, inplace=True)
  • printing: df.iloc[20,:]

Calculated columns

  • df[calculated_column]=df[column1]+df[column2]: new column is the sum of two existing columns
  • df[calculated_column]=df.column1*df.column2: new column is the product of two existing columns
  • df[calculated_column]=pow(df.column1, 2): new column is the power of two of the column1

Lab

  • Take birthCountry, height and weight from the Master DF.
  • Replace NA with average values of height and weight.
  • Tranform weight from pounds to kg and height from inches to meters
  • Calculate BMI and show 10 rows
  • Calculate average BMI index by birthCountry, sort by birthCountry

Solution

  • averageW=df[“weight”].mean()
  • averageH=df[“height”].mean()
  • df.weight.fillna(averageW, inplace=True)
  • df.height.fillna(averageH, inplace=True)
  • df[“weightKG”]=df.weight/2.2
  • df[“heightCM”]=df.height*2.54
  • df[“BMI”]=df[“weightKG”]/(df[“heightCM”]/100*df[“heightCM”]/100)
  • df1=df[[“birthCountry”,“weightKG”,“heightCM”,“BMI”]]
  • df1=df1.groupby(“birthCountry”).mean()
  • df1.sort_values(“birthCountry”)

“Case when”

  • there isn’t really case when statement in pandas
  • work around with numpy
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

data=pd.read_excel("./Lab/Datasets/cars.xlsx")

conditions = [
    (data["Quantity"].le(400)),
    (data["Quantity"].between(400,700)),
    (data["Quantity"].gt(700))]
choices = ["small", "medium", "high"]

data["Quantity_r"] = np.select(conditions, choices)
data.Quantity_r.value_counts()
## small     2356
## medium     286
## high        52

import pandas as pd

Using apply and lambda with pandas (1)

  • sometimes simple method will not work:
df=pd.read_csv("Master.csv")
df["birthYear"]=df["birthYear"].astype(int)
  • Error:Cannot convert non-finite values (NA or inf) to integer
  • you can use fillna, but sometimes you don’t want it
  • alternative: apply and lambda

Using apply and lambda with pandas (2)

df["birthYear"]=df["birthYear"].apply(
lambda x: int(x) if not np.isnan(x) else x 
)

Using apply and lambda with pandas (3)

  • more complex logic, i.e. combining multiple columns:
def someStupidLogic(birthYear,birthCountry,birthState):
    if birthYear<1950 and not pd.isnull(birthCountry):
        result=str(birthYear)+" "+birthCountry
    elif birthYear<2000 and birthYear>=1950 and not pd.isnull(birthState):
        result=str(birthYear)+" "+birthState
    else:
        result=str(birthYear)+" Random place"
    return result
  
df["someStupidLogic"]=df.apply(lambda x:
someStupidLogic(x["birthYear"], 
                x["birthCountry"],
                x["birthState"])
                         ,axis=1)

Merge dataframes

  • database-style DataFrame or named Series joining/merging
  • pd.merge
  • default: inner join
  • result = pd.merge(left, right, on=‘key’, how=“inner”)
  • joining on many columns: pd.merge(left, right, on=[column1, column2])
  • joining on many columns with different names: pd.merge(left, right, left_on==[column1, column2], right_on= [column3, column4])

Example

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

df1 = pd.DataFrame({'ID': [1,2,3,4,5,6], 'pID' : [21,22,23,24,25,26], 
'Values1' : [435,33,45,34,57,12]})

df2 = pd.DataFrame({'ID' : [4,4,5], 'pid' : [24,25,25], 
'Values2' : [544, 545, 676]})

result=pd.merge(df1, df2, left_on=['ID', 'pID'], right_on=['ID', 'pid'])

print(result)
##    ID  pID  Values1  pid  Values2
## 0   4   24       34   24      544
## 1   5   25       57   25      676

Seaborn

Modules

  • Matplotlib
  • Seaborn: targets statistical data visualization
  • Seaborn is complimentary to Matplotlib
  • Seaborn:
    • creates aesthetically pleasing plots by default
    • creates statistically meaningful plots
    • understands the pandas DataFrame
    • is not directly included in Anaconda’s release

Seaborn plots

  • broadly divided into two classes:
    • “Axes-level” functions: regplot, boxplot, kdeplot
    • “Figure-level” functions: lmplot, factorplot, jointplot
  • axes-level functions will only draw onto an axes and won’t otherwise mess with the figure
  • figure level: the functions need to have total control over the figure
  • figure level: fig and axes arguments, customization has to come after you’ve called the function

Statistically meaningful plots

Linear regression

  • lmplot
  • regplot
  • parameters:
    • hue: color by categories
    • col/row: facets
    • fit_reg: regression line
    • ci: confidential intervals
    • order: polyinominal fitting curve

Lab

Import CarsCSV.csv and show Quantity by Manufacturer and Year (facet). Show only data for Volkswagen, Toyota and Skoda for year 2007 and 2008. Mind the whitespace after the value in columns. Use str.strip() to trim.

Solution

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

df=pd.read_csv("./Lab/Datasets/CarsCSV.csv")

df=df[["Year","Manufacturer","Quantity"]]

df=df[(df["Manufacturer"].str.strip()=="Toyota") | 
(df["Manufacturer"].str.strip()=="Volkswagen") | 
(df["Manufacturer"].str.strip()=="Skoda")]

df=df[(df["Year"]==2007) | (df["Year"]==2008)]

df=df.groupby(["Manufacturer","Year"], as_index=False).sum()

sns.catplot(x="Manufacturer", y="Quantity",  kind="bar", col="Year", data=df, height=3)
